{"findings":[{"problem":"Missing `.remove` callback in `ras2_mem_driver` causes resource leaks and a guaranteed kernel panic on module unload.","severity":"High","severity_explanation":"The auxiliary driver `ras2_mem_driver` registers an EDAC device using `edac_dev_register()` in its `.probe` callback but fails to implement a `.remove` callback. If the module is unloaded or the device is unbound, `edac_dev_unregister()` is never called, leaving sysfs nodes pointing to unmapped module text. Furthermore, the driver spawns `ras2_scrub_monitor_thread` via `kthread_run()` but discards the `task_struct` pointer, making it impossible to stop the thread. Upon module unload, the unstopped kthread will attempt to execute freed module memory, resulting in a use-after-free kernel panic."},{"problem":"Race condition when starting `ras2_scrub_monitor_thread` breaks background scrub resumption and state tracking.","severity":"High","severity_explanation":"In `ras2_hw_scrub_set_enabled_od()`, when preempting a background scrub, the monitor thread is spawned via `kthread_run()` before the main thread acquires `pcc_lock` and updates the hardware state or sets `ras2_ctx->od_scrub = true`. The new kthread runs immediately, acquires `pcc_lock`, and calls `ras2_get_demand_scrub_running()`. Since `od_scrub` is still false, the thread mistakenly concludes the demand scrub has already finished, prematurely restarts the background scrub, and exits. The main thread then overwrites the hardware to start the demand scrub. This leaves the hardware running a demand scrub while the software falsely reports background scrub is active, and without the monitor thread, the background scrub will never resume once the demand scrub actually completes."},{"problem":"Missing `pcc_lock` in sysfs read paths causes data races on the `__iomem` PCC shared memory.","severity":"High","severity_explanation":"Both `ras2_hw_scrub_read_addr()` and `ras2_hw_scrub_read_size()` call `ras2_update_patrol_scrub_params_cache()` without acquiring `ras2_ctx->pcc_lock`. The cache update function writes to the hardware shared memory (`ps_sm->params.command = RAS2_GET_PATROL_PARAMETERS`, etc.) and sends a PCC command. Concurrent sysfs reads, or reads occurring during a write operation (e.g., `set_enabled_od`), will interleave modifications to the shared communication buffer. This corrupts the payload sent to the hardware and will cause unpredictable hardware behavior."},{"problem":"Missing upper bound validation for demand scrub `size` allows arbitrary physical memory access.","severity":"High","severity_explanation":"In `ras2_hw_scrub_set_enabled_od()`, the address range validation only verifies that `ras2_ctx->base >= ras2_ctx->mem_base`. It fails to check if the user-supplied `ras2_ctx->size` causes integer wrap-around or exceeds the valid NUMA node boundary (`ras2_ctx->mem_base + ras2_ctx->mem_size`). This allows userspace to instruct the hardware scrubbing engine to access arbitrary physical addresses outside the designated domain, potentially hitting MMIO ranges or secure memory, leading to a system crash (machine check) or denial of service."},{"problem":"Reading `addr` or `size` sysfs attributes silently destroys staged scrub cycle configurations.","severity":"Medium","severity_explanation":"When a user configures `current_cycle_duration`, the value is staged in `ras2_ctx->scrub_cycle_hrs` until a scrub is started. However, if the user then reads the `addr` or `size` attributes, the driver calls `ras2_update_patrol_scrub_params_cache()`. This function unconditionally fetches the hardware's active parameters and executes `ras2_ctx->scrub_cycle_hrs = FIELD_GET(...)`, silently overwriting and destroying the user's staged configuration."},{"problem":"Lockless modification of `base` and `size` in `ras2_scrub_monitor_thread` causes data races with user configuration.","severity":"Medium","severity_explanation":"In `ras2_scrub_monitor_thread()`, when the demand scrub completes (`running =